{
  "doc_id": "22136",
  "text": "There are several difficulties with this theory. Unemployment in urban sectors of poor countries is not particularly high-certainly not high enough to explain large wage gaps [CITATION_1] and [CITATION_2] ). There is also disguised or unmeasured unemployment in rural sectors [CITATION_3] ). Thus, there is less of an urban unemployment problem when viewed relative to the actual unemployment in the rural sector. We do not focus on the higher probability of facing unemployment in urban areas as a reason for the wage gap. However, we do add migration costs, as an extension to our model, and one interpretation of these costs is that it is hard for rural migrants to find steady employment in the city.",
